{
  "category": "Uncategorized",
  "description": "Email AI Triage & Intelligence Layer\n\nImplement an AI-powered email triage system that brings Superhuman-style intelligence to the unified inbox — automatically summarizing long emails and threads, surfacing contextual signals, and enabling AI-drafted replies — so users can process high email volume in a fraction of the time.\n\n---\n\nOVERVIEW\n\nThe inbox is a high-noise, high-stakes surface. Users currently must open and read every email in full to determine its importance and required action. This feature introduces an AI layer that pre-processes incoming emails and threads, extracts the signal from the noise, and reduces the cognitive load of inbox zero to a series of quick decisions rather than full reads.\n\nBecause Krisp already stores emails in Neon PostgreSQL and has OpenAI embeddings infrastructure in place, this triage layer can be built on top of existing data pipelines without re-ingesting messages.\n\n---\n\nREQUIREMENTS\n\n1. Per-Email AI Summary Card\n- When a user opens an email, display a collapsed \"AI Summary\" panel above the message body\n- Summarize the email in 2–4 bullet points covering: what is being asked, who sent it and why it matters, any deadlines or urgency signals, and what action (if any) is required\n- For short emails (under ~200 words), suppress the summary panel automatically — it adds no value\n- Show a confidence indicator or \"Generated from full message\" attribution so users trust the output\n- Cache the summary in the database against the email record to avoid re-generating on every open\n\n2. Thread Summarization\n- For email threads with 3 or more messages, show a \"Summarize thread\" trigger at the top of the conversation view\n- The summary should capture: the original ask, key decisions or agreements reached, who said what (attributed), outstanding open questions, and the most recent status\n- Thread summary must update when a new reply arrives (invalidate and regenerate, or append a delta)\n- Surface a \"Jump to what matters\" anchor that scrolls to the most action-relevant message in the thread\n\n3. Importance & Urgency Signals\n- Analyze each email for signals: explicit deadlines (\"by Friday\", \"EOD\"), sender VIP status (based on email frequency or user-defined contacts), urgency language, and whether the user is directly addressed vs. CC'd\n- Assign a computed triage score (high / medium / low) and surface it as a visual badge on the inbox list view\n- Do not override the user — the score is advisory, not prescriptive\n- Allow users to give thumbs-up / thumbs-down feedback on triage accuracy to fine-tune future scoring\n\n4. AI Draft Reply\n- Add a \"Draft reply with AI\" action to each email and thread\n- The draft should: match the tone of the original email (formal vs. casual), reference specific asks or questions from the sender, and be appropriately concise\n- Present the draft in an editable composer — never send automatically\n- Support follow-up prompts: \"make it shorter\", \"add an apology\", \"be more assertive\" — one-shot refinement via a prompt input below the draft\n- If the email contains an action item or commitment in the draft, offer to create a linked Kanban card or action item record before sending\n\n5. Context Surfacing (Open Brain Integration)\n- Before displaying a draft or summary, query the Open Brain memory store for related context: prior conversations with this sender, relevant Kanban cards, meeting transcripts where this sender or topic appeared, or captured thoughts tagged to similar subjects\n- Surface up to 3 contextual memory hits as a collapsible \"Related context\" panel alongside the email\n- Each memory hit should link back to its source (meeting, card, thought capture) for one-click navigation\n\n6. Triage Queue Mode\n- Add an optional \"Triage mode\" view to the inbox — a focused, card-by-card interface similar to a flashcard deck\n- Each card shows: sender, subject, AI summary, triage score, and four quick actions: Archive, Reply with Draft, Create Action Item, Snooze\n- Users move through their inbox at pace without opening individual email views\n- Track triage session stats (emails processed, time taken, actions taken) for display in the AI Weekly Productivity Report integration\n\n---\n\nDATA & STORAGE\n\n- Add a nullable ai_summary column (text) and triage_score column (enum: high / medium / low / unscored) to the emails table via Drizzle migration\n- Add a thread_summary column keyed to a thread ID grouping\n- Store draft reply text ephemerally in client state only — do not persist unsent drafts unless explicitly saved by the user\n- Log triage feedback (thumbs up/down) to a separate email_triage_feedback table for future fine-tuning\n\n---\n\nAI MODEL USAGE\n\n- Use Claude (claude-sonnet-4) for summarization, triage scoring, and draft generation — consistent with existing meeting search implementation\n- Structure prompts to return structured JSON outputs (summary bullets, score, draft body) for reliable parsing\n- Apply a token budget per email to control cost: summaries capped at ~300 output tokens, drafts at ~500 tokens\n- Batch-generate summaries for unread emails in the background on inbox load rather than at open time, using a queue to avoid rate limit spikes\n\n---\n\nEDGE CASES\n\n- Emails with only attachments and no body: summarize based on subject line, sender, and attachment filenames only; label as \"Limited context\"\n- Non-English emails: detect language, summarize in English with a language attribution note, draft reply in the original language\n- Forwarded emails or automated notifications (receipts, alerts, newsletters): detect and suppress the draft reply option; apply a \"No reply needed\" triage badge\n- Very long threads (20+ messages): summarize only the last 10 messages plus the original, with a note that earlier context was truncated\n- Emails containing sensitive content (PII patterns, financial data): summarize at topic level only, do not quote verbatim in the summary panel\n\n---\n\nSUCCESS CRITERIA\n\n- A user can determine the required action of any email without reading the full body\n- Draft replies require no more than one refinement prompt before being send-ready in the majority of cases\n- Triage queue mode allows processing of 20 unread emails in under 3 minutes\n- AI summaries and scores are rated accurate by the user (thumbs-up) at a rate exceeding 80% after an initial calibration period\n- Zero emails are sent automatically — all AI actions require explicit user confirmation",
